# Frontend Architecture

This rule describes the approved architecture for this project specifically. It supersedes any generic frontend pattern that conflicts with what is written here.

**Rule precedence (full chain):**
`story-driven-development.mdc` → `product-owner.mdc` → `mvp-guardrail.mdc` → `workflow.mdc` → `coding-standards.mdc` → `frontend-architecture.mdc` (this file) → `testing.mdc`

---

## Folder Structure

```
src/
├── pages/
│   ├── home/
│   │   └── HomePage.tsx
│   ├── configure/
│   │   ├── ConfigurePage.tsx        # Thin route wrapper
│   │   ├── CombinationForm.tsx      # Owns all four inputs and form state
│   │   ├── PrinterSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── MaterialSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── NozzleSelector.tsx
│   │   ├── GoalSelector.tsx
│   │   └── availability.ts          # isAvailable(p, m, n, g) → boolean — no UI
│   └── profile/
│       ├── ProfilePage.tsx           # Thin route wrapper
│       ├── ProfileCard.tsx
│       ├── DownloadButton.tsx
│       ├── ImportGuide.tsx
│       └── FeedbackPrompt.tsx
│
├── shared/                           # Design system only — zero product logic
│   ├── Button.tsx
│   ├── Card.tsx
│   ├── SegmentedSelector.tsx
│   ├── SearchableDropdown.tsx
│   └── PageLayout.tsx
│
├── hooks/
│   └── useProfileStats.ts            # The only shared hook at MVP
│
├── lib/
│   ├── slug.ts                       # encode/decode combination slugs
│   └── url-params.ts                 # parse /configure query params
│
├── types.ts                          # ALL domain types and constants — one file
├── App.tsx                           # Router + QueryClientProvider
└── main.tsx
```

**Boundary rules:**

- Feature components live inside their page directory. There is no `features/` directory.
- `src/shared/` components have zero knowledge of domain entities. `SegmentedSelector` does not know it is displaying materials. Domain labels are applied at the page layer.
- `src/types.ts` imports from nothing in the project. It is the dependency root.
- `scripts/engine/types.ts` contains engine-internal types only. It never imports from `src/`.

---

## Routing

Three routes. Configured in `App.tsx`.

```
/                       → HomePage
/configure              → ConfigurePage
/profile/:slug          → ProfilePage
```

`App.tsx` is also where `QueryClientProvider` is mounted. It is 20–30 lines at MVP. It does not need to be split into `router.tsx` and `providers.tsx`.

---

## Page Structure

**Page components are thin route wrappers.** `ConfigurePage.tsx` and `ProfilePage.tsx` render the layout wrapper and their primary feature component. They contain no logic.

**`CombinationForm.tsx`** is the only component that owns the full combination selection state (all four inputs). It:
- derives the slicer format from the selected printer
- derives the resolved slug from all four inputs
- controls the generate button state
- delegates navigation on submit

**`availability.ts`** is a module, not a component. It exports `isAvailable(printer, material, nozzle, goal): boolean`. It loads the manifest once and holds it in a module-level cache. It has no UI and no React dependency.

---

## State Ownership

The URL is the single source of truth for the current combination.

| State | Owner | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Form inputs (4 values) | `CombinationForm` local state | Initialized from URL query params on mount |
| Slicer format | Derived from printer in `CombinationForm` | Not shown in the UI at MVP |
| Combination manifest | Module-level cache in `availability.ts` | One fetch per page load; never re-fetched |
| Profile static data (title, highlights, file path) | Embedded in the page via SSG | Never fetched at runtime |
| Confidence count | TanStack Query — `useProfileStats(slug)` | Fetched on mount; does not block render |
| `hasDownloaded` | `DownloadButton` local state | Drives `ImportGuide` and `FeedbackPrompt` visibility |
| Feedback outcome | `FeedbackPrompt` local state | Shows confirmation on submit |

**There is no global store.** Zustand is not installed and is not used at MVP. If a component needs state, it owns it locally. The conditions for a global store — shared UI state across multiple routes, user account state — do not exist at MVP.

---

## React Query

React Query is used for exactly **one** query at MVP: `useProfileStats`.

```typescript
// src/hooks/useProfileStats.ts
export function useProfileStats(slug: string) {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['profile-stats', slug],
    queryFn: () =>
      fetch(`/api/profile/${slug}/stats`).then(r => r.json()),
    staleTime: 1000 * 60,
  });
}
```

`QueryClientProvider` is mounted once in `App.tsx`.

Do not use React Query for manifest loading. The manifest is a static file loaded once with a plain `fetch` inside `availability.ts`. It does not need caching, refetching, or loading states.

Do not introduce additional React Query hooks until a second async data requirement exists.

---

## Manifest Consumption

`generated/combinations.json` is a static file served from the CDN. It is the source of truth for which combinations are available and their metadata.

**How it is consumed:**

```typescript
// src/pages/configure/availability.ts
let manifest: Manifest | null = null;

async function loadManifest(): Promise<Manifest> {
  if (!manifest) {
    manifest = await fetch('/combinations.json').then(r => r.json());
  }
  return manifest;
}

export async function isAvailable(
  printer: string,
  material: string,
  nozzle: string,
  goal: string,
): Promise<boolean> {
  const m = await loadManifest();
  return m.combinations.some(
    c => c.printer === printer && c.material === material &&
         c.nozzle === nozzle && c.goal === goal && c.isAvailable,
  );
}
```

The manifest is loaded once on the Configure page and held in a module-level variable. There is no TanStack Query wrapper for it and no React state. It is a static file — a `fetch` with a module-level cache is sufficient.

---

## API Boundaries

Two runtime endpoints exist at MVP:

| Endpoint | Method | Called from | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `/combinations.json` | GET (static) | `availability.ts` | Served from CDN — not a server route |
| `/api/profile/:slug/stats` | GET | `useProfileStats` | Returns `{ confidenceCount: number }` |
| `/api/feedback` | POST | `FeedbackPrompt` | Returns `{ ok: true }` |

**There is no `api` module abstraction.** Two endpoints do not justify a typed wrapper. Calls are made with plain `fetch` at the call site. If a third endpoint is added and the pattern repeats, extract then.

**There is no `/api/generate` endpoint at MVP.** Slug construction happens client-side in `CombinationForm`. The slug is deterministic: `[printer]-[material]-[nozzle]-[goal]`. The form validates against the manifest client-side before navigating.

---

## Component Organization

Components inside a page directory are colocated with their page. They are peers of the page component — they change together.

```
// ✅ — colocated, changed together
src/pages/configure/CombinationForm.tsx
src/pages/configure/PrinterSelector.tsx
src/pages/configure/availability.ts

// ❌ — no features/ directory
src/features/configure/components/CombinationForm.tsx
```

A component moves to `src/shared/` only when it has zero domain knowledge. `SegmentedSelector` receives `options` and `value` — it does not know what materials are. `SearchableDropdown` receives an `items` array — it does not know what printers are. Domain binding happens in `MaterialSelector.tsx` and `PrinterSelector.tsx`.

If a component is only used in one place and contains product logic, it stays in its page directory. The refactor to shared is cheap when the time comes.

---

## File Naming

| What | Convention |
|---|---|
| Page components | `PascalCase.tsx` (`ConfigurePage.tsx`) |
| Feature components | `PascalCase.tsx` (`CombinationForm.tsx`) |
| Shared components | `PascalCase.tsx` (`SegmentedSelector.tsx`) |
| Hooks | `use` + `PascalCase.ts` (`useProfileStats.ts`) |
| Pure utilities | `camelCase.ts` (`slug.ts`, `url-params.ts`) |
| Non-UI modules | `camelCase.ts` (`availability.ts`) |
| Tests | `<filename>.test.ts(x)` colocated |
| Types file | `types.ts` (singular, at `src/types.ts`) |

---

## What Does NOT Exist at MVP

This is a hard list. If an agent suggests any of the following, it is out of scope.

| Pattern | Why it does not exist |
|---|---|
| `src/features/` | The project uses `src/pages/` — approved in `folder-structure.md` |
| `src/store/` | No global store; Zustand is not installed |
| `src/types/` directory | `src/types.ts` is a single file by explicit architectural decision |
| Storybook | Not in the spec; not in any story |
| `api.ts` per page/feature | Two direct `fetch` calls do not require an abstraction layer |
| `src/lib/httpClient.ts` | Not needed; plain `fetch` is sufficient |
| `POST /api/generate` | Client-side slug construction replaces it |
| `forwardRef` | React 19 — `ref` is a prop |
| Multiple `QueryClientProvider` instances | One, in `App.tsx` |

---

## Expansion Path After MVP

When Phase 1 work begins, these are the expected structural changes and where they land:

| Phase 1 addition | Where it goes |
|---|---|
| User accounts | New `src/pages/account/` route; Zustand slice added to `src/stores/` |
| Stats API goes live | `useProfileStats` already exists — no structural change |
| Additional shared components | `src/shared/` grows; no restructuring needed |
| `src/types.ts` grows past ~150 lines | Split into `src/types/domain.ts`, `src/types/manifest.ts` — mechanical refactor |
| Second shared hook | `src/hooks/` already exists — add alongside `useProfileStats` |
| Slicer override UI | Add `SlicerOverride.tsx` to `src/pages/configure/` |

No structural change is needed for Phase 1 unless user accounts are introduced. The current structure supports it without pre-emptive abstraction.
